Why America Should Not Reelect President Bush
I have never particularly engaged in party politics, but these are not normal times.
President George W. Bush endangers the security of the United States and the world and simultaneously undermines American values.
Due to my opposition to him, I have been demonized by Bush's campaign team.
President Bush ran in 2000 on a platform promising a foreign policy of "humble" diplomacy.
If he is re-elected, this will be a vote for the Bush doctrine of preemptive war - and the invasion of Iraq - and the world will have to live with the consequences.
By rejecting Bush's policy at the ballot boxes, America has a chance to regain the respect and support of the world.
The terrorist attacks of September 11, 2001, required a strong response.
They have however also led to the suspension of the critical process so indispensable to democracy - the comprehensive and honest discussion of pending issues.
Bush has silenced criticism by labeling it unpatriotic.
For the duration of 18 months following September 11, he succeeded in suppressing all dissent.
In this way, he led America in the wrong direction.
In fact, Bush played directly into Osama bin Laden's hands.
The invasion of Afghanistan - where bin Laden lived and Al Qaeda maintained its training camps - was justified.
The invasion of Iraq was not.
He was Bush's unintended gift to bin Laden.
Immediately following September 11, spontaneous expressions of sympathy for America emerged all over the world.
These have given way to widespread bitterness.
Clearly more people today are willing to risk their lives to kill Americans than were on September 11.
Bush likes to claim that terrorists hate Americans for what they are - a freedom-loving people - and not for what they do.
War and occupation, however, produce innocent victims.
We Americans count our fallen soldiers - more than 1,000 in Iraq.
The rest of the world also counts the Iraqis killed every day - perhaps twenty times as many.
The torture of prisoners at Abu Ghraib prison was also not the work of a few "bad apples".
It was part of a system established by Defense Secretary Donald Rumsfeld for dealing with prisoners.
The world public condemns America, and our troops in Iraq are paying the price for it.
Bush has convinced people that America's security is in good hands by addressing the fears caused by the attacks of September 11th.
In times of danger, people gather around their flag, and Bush has exploited this by fostering a sense of threat.
His campaign assumes that people ultimately do not care about the truth and will believe almost anything if it is repeated often enough.
Something is not right with America if we fall for this.
For example, about 40% of all Americans still believe that Saddam Hussein had something to do with September 11th, even though the 9/11 Commission - appointed by Bush and chaired by a Republican - clearly established that no such connection existed.
One wants to shout: "Wake up, America.
Don't you realize that we are being led astray?"
The war in Iraq was based on false premises from beginning to end - if it ever finds an end.
It was a war of one's own choosing, not out of necessity.
Moreover, America entered the war under a pretext: weapons of mass destruction could not be found, and the connection to Al Qaeda cannot be proven.
Bush then claimed that America had gone to war to free Iraq.
But democracy cannot be imposed on anyone by force.
Saddam Hussein was a tyrant, and the Iraqis - and the world - can be glad to be rid of him.
America, however, had the duty to ensure justice and order; instead, we stood idly by as Baghdad and other cities were looted.
If we had really cared about the Iraqi people, we would have had to provide a larger number of soldiers for the occupation.
We would have had to protect not only the Ministry of Oil, but also other ministries, museums, and hospitals.
Worse still: Where American soldiers encountered resistance, they used methods - such as entering private homes and mistreating prisoners - that shocked and humiliated the population and thus provoked bitterness and anger.
The retreats and missteps of the Bush administration are legion.
First, the Iraqi army was disbanded, then America tried to rebuild it.
First, the USA tried to eliminate the Baathists, then America sought their help.
When the uprisings could no longer be controlled, America installed an Iraqi government.
The man chosen as their leader was a CIA protege with the reputation of a "strong man" - anything but a democratic decision.
Despite the efforts of Bush's campaign team to spin the situation, the situation in Iraq is bleak.
A large part of the western part of the country was left to the insurgents. The prospects for holding free and fair elections in January are rapidly diminishing.
Civil war threatens.
Bush's war in Iraq has also caused immense damage to America, weakened its military strength, and undermined the morale of the troops.
Before the war, America could project an image of overwhelming strength.
Today, it cannot anymore.
Afghanistan is slipping out of control.
North Korea, Iran, Pakistan, and other countries are pursuing nuclear programs with renewed energy.
One can criticize the Bush administration on many other political issues, but none is as significant as Iraq.
The cost of the war so far amounts to nearly 200 billion dollars and will continue to rise, because the invasion of Iraq was much easier than the withdrawal will be.
Bush has challenged John Kerry to explain what he would have done differently.
Kerry responded that he would have done everything differently and that he would be in a better position to free us from our entanglement.
But this will not be easy for him either, because America is stuck in a quagmire.
Leading military experts and diplomats have urgently warned Bush not to march into Iraq.
He ignored them.
He suppressed the critical process with the argument that any criticism of the commander-in-chief would endanger US troops.
But this is Bush's war, and he should be held accountable for it.
The Americans should take a moment to pause and ask themselves: To whom do we owe this mess?
A moment of reflection should raise another question: Does Bush's cowboy behavior qualify him to remain America's supreme commander?
